ADVANCED INSTRUCTIONS\
\
1) Create MIAP IN midi track into Ableton:\
The MIDI MIAP max patch uses midi device channel 5 to send the X and Y coordinates to Ableton. In ableton, open a new midi track, and disable any midi output. Then select midi input from Max1 and channel 5.\
\
2) Create MIAP OUT midi track into Ableton:\
The MIDI MIAP max patch uses midi device channel 5 to receive the X and Y coordinates to Ableton. In ableton, open a new midi track, and disable any midi input. Then select midi output to Max1 and channel 5.\
\
3) Create an audio track, name it AUDIO.\
\
4) Create an empty send.\
\
5) Create any number of audio tracks between 1 and 24. These are going to be your physical outputs from your sound card, so define the outputs of each track in chronological order. Group these tracks and name the group Output... select all the tracks in the group and choose the input for these tracks to be the empty send you created before.\
\
6) You will need to map the track volume slider of each track in the Output group. To help this process, use the AUTO MAP ON OFF toggle button in the MIDI MIAP max patch. This will go through all of the 1 to 24 outputs in chronological order, and "move each fader a little" every three seconds. This is a bit tricky, but is still the easy way to map everything. Lets begin\
		\
--> Press cmd + m in ableton and have your OUTPUT group open, so you see all the tracks. Click the first track in the group. \
		\
--> Press the AUTO MAP toggle in the MIDI MIAP patch. Go quickly to Ableton and you will see that the slider got mapped. Quickly press the next volume slider and wait for it to be mapped. Do this for all the tracks, and once you are done, click somewhere else in Ableton, so that the next "map message" doesn't mess up your important mappings. \
\
--> Go quickly to the MIDI MIAP patch and turn the AUTO MAP Toggle button off. Go to Ableton and press cmd + m again to get out from the midi mapping state.\
\
7) Now you are done! Play any sounds into the send channel. And go to the MIDI MIAP patch. Move the point in the map A, and the sound should pan to the corresponding output. You can record the trajectory into the MIAP IN midi track and play it back in the MIAP OUT midi track.\
\
8) Enjoy and explore!\
